        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15716\">#15716</a> I prove that </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">birthday_add_le</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Game</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">♯</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>where <code>♯</code> is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/SetTheory/Ordinal/NaturalOps.html#Ordinal.nadd\">natural addition</a>. I'm wondering if there's any analogous version for multiplication, namely</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">birthday_mul_le</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Surreal</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⨳</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">birthday</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>where <code>⨳</code> is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/SetTheory/Ordinal/NaturalOps.html#Ordinal.nmul\">natural multiplication</a>, but I'm coming up blank. I haven't been able to find a reference, nor to prove this myself.</p>",
        "id": 461967775,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723500525
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This result is important since it allows proving the subset of games with birthday less than <code>ω^ω^o</code> forms a ring.</p>",
        "id": 461968034,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723500675
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(at least, if I'm correct about it)</p>",
        "id": 461968306,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723500847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The problem is that a priori, the games xᴸy + xyᴸ – xᴸyᴸ, etc. seem like they should have a birthday at least thrice that of xᴸyᴸ. In fact, for the pre-game birthday, this is the case, which makes that version of the theorem false.</p>",
        "id": 461968985,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723501266
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is an open problem <span aria-label=\"sob\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f62d\" role=\"img\" title=\"sob\">:sob:</span><br>\n<a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/476829/147705\">https://mathoverflow.net/a/476829/147705</a></p>",
        "id": 462013366,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723522188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is the weaker result in the edit (<code>(x * y).birthday &lt;= omega ⨳ x.birthday ⨳ x.birthday ⨳ y.birthday ⨳ y.birthday</code>) sufficient to prove your theorem about games up to <code>ω^ω^o</code> forming a ring?</p>",
        "id": 462196361,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1723577093
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is, and that's actually what they do in the paper</p>",
        "id": 462227177,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1723591139
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It requires expanding the surreals into a \"Conway form\" though, so it's going to be a while until we get there</p>",
